{
  "texts": [
    "These constraints imply that there exists some scalar γ, such that e -2Φ B = dγ.",
    "We shall assume that this constraint is trivial everywhere on the worldsheet, except when C is a boundary of one of the M removed discs D a -we will denote such constraints by S a.",
    "18 The condition is non-trivial at these points since (focusing on the holomorphic sector) they correspond to where β = 0 whilst e -2Φ simultaneously diverges at these points.If we were to impose the constraint e -2Φ B = dγ, the action becomes the familiar non-linear sigma modelS AdS 3 = - 1 4π d 2 z 2∂Φ ∂Φ + e 2Φ ∂γ ∂γ.The equivalence to the standard WZW model demonstrates that the theory is non-chiral throughout.",
    "More precisely, in passing from the NLSM to the WZW model the change of variables from γ to B requires a Jacobian det(e 2Φ d) in the functional integral, which can be incorporated into the action (2.25) as an anomaly termS W = - 1 4π d 2 z 4∂Φ ∂Φ + β ∂γ + ΦR, (2.27)where R is the worldsheet Ricci scalar.",
    "The change of variables only makes sense on those points where B ̸ = 0 and so the Jacobian is only defined away from those points (which have been removed).The delta functions that constrain B areδ 2 e -2Φ B = δ e -2Φ β δ e -2Φ β.Following [50], we claim then that the Wakimoto theory requires the constraint (2.26) and correlation functions are calculated by 19 DΦDβD βDγ e -S W [β,γ,Φ]N a=1 δ Ca e -2Φ β δ Ca e -2Φ β n i=1 O i (Φ, β, β, γ) (2.28)18 It is clearly sufficient to apply these constraints to the non-contractible cycles."
